#  Day 50 – Task S-4 (Part 1): Documenting Control Implementation in the System Security Plan | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## Day 50: From Decisions to Documentation

Fifty days in. The Prepare step built the organizational foundation. The Categorize step produced the High categorization and the official categorization record. The Select step produced the tailored control set, the allocation decisions, and now — Task S-4 — the implementation documentation that turns all of that analysis into the System Security Plan.

The SSP is the document that makes the authorization decision possible. When the Authorizing Official reviews the authorization package and decides whether to grant an Authorization to Operate, the SSP is the primary reference. It needs to answer, for every control in the tailored set: what is implemented, who implemented it, where it is implemented, how it works, and how it can be verified. Those are not rhetorical questions — they are the literal questions an assessor will work through during the security assessment.

Today I work through how to write SSP control implementation descriptions that actually serve those purposes — not just acknowledge that a control exists.

---

## What I Worked On Today

NIST SP 800-18 provides the framework for SSP content and structure. For each control, the SSP implementation description needs to address: the control requirement, the implementation status (implemented, partially implemented, planned, not applicable, inherited), and a description of how the control is implemented with enough specificity to support assessment.

"Enough specificity to support assessment" is the operative phrase. An assessor who reads the SSP description needs to know what evidence to request and what to test. An implementation description that says "encryption is enabled" does not tell the assessor whether to look at RDS instance settings, KMS key configuration, or EBS volume settings — or all three. An implementation description that says "RDS encryption is enabled via AWS KMS using customer-managed key arn:aws:kms:[region]:[account]:key/[key-id]; EBS volumes are encrypted using the same customer-managed key; S3 backup bucket uses SSE-KMS with the same key; key rotation is configured for annual rotation; key usage is logged in CloudTrail log group [log-group-name]" tells the assessor exactly what to verify and where to find the evidence.

The gap between those two descriptions is the gap between an SSP that enables assessment and one that creates work for everyone and produces unnecessary findings.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The framing that clarified SSP writing for me today is that an SSP implementation description is simultaneously a claim and a roadmap to verify that claim.

When I write "RDS encryption is enabled," I am making a claim that the assessor will need to verify. If the description includes enough detail to guide the verification — which service, which setting, which key, where the logs are — the assessment proceeds efficiently and the control is demonstrated. If the description is vague, the assessor has to ask clarifying questions, request additional documentation, or mark the implementation status as unclear — none of which helps the authorization package.

Writing with verification in mind changes the level of detail naturally. Instead of "MFA is enabled," the SSP author asks: "What would an assessor need to verify that MFA is enabled and functioning correctly?" The answer is: which MFA method, for which users, how it is configured, what happens when MFA fails, and how exceptions are handled. Each of those questions points to a detail that belongs in the implementation description.

This also makes the SSP a useful diagnostic tool for the security program. When writing the implementation description, if the answer to "where is this logged?" is "I'm not sure," or the answer to "how is this reviewed?" is "we haven't defined that process yet," the SSP writing has surfaced a gap — exactly as it should.

