### Access Control (AC) — Application Layer

---

**AC-2: Account Management**

**Implementation Status:** Implemented

**Implementation Description:**

Account lifecycle management for OpenMRS follows a documented procedure:

*Account provisioning:* New account requests submitted to Health IT Manager via documented request form specifying user identity, role required, and business justification. Health IT Manager approves or rejects within one business day. ISSO creates the account in OpenMRS with the approved role. User receives activation email with temporary password and MFA enrollment instructions. Account is not considered active until MFA enrollment is confirmed.

*Account modification:* Role changes require the same approval process as new account creation. Emergency role changes (e.g., covering for an absent clinician) require verbal Health IT Manager approval followed by written confirmation within 24 hours.

*Account deactivation:* HR notifies ISSO of employee separations via a defined notification process. ISSO disables the account within 4 hours of notification. Account is disabled (not deleted) to preserve audit trail. ISSO confirms deactivation in writing to HR and Health IT Manager.

*Account review:* Quarterly access review conducted by ISSO. ISSO produces a report of all active accounts with their roles and last login date. Health IT Manager reviews and certifies that each account is still needed and appropriately configured. Any accounts not recertified are deactivated within 5 business days.

*Privileged accounts:* IT Administrator and ISSO accounts are reviewed monthly, not quarterly. Privileged account usage logs are reviewed within 24 hours of generation.

**Assessment Evidence:** Account provisioning request forms for most recent three accounts; quarterly access review report and Health IT Manager certification; deactivation records for most recent five employee separations with timestamps; privileged account review records.

---

**AC-3: Access Enforcement (Role-Based Access Control)**

**Implementation Status:** Implemented

**Implementation Description:**

Access to OpenMRS functionality and patient data is enforced through OpenMRS's built-in role-based access control system. The following roles are configured:

*Clinician role:* Access to patient registration, encounter documentation, medication management, care plan management, and clinical reporting for patients within the clinician's care relationship. Cannot access other clinicians' patient panels without explicit authorization. Cannot access system administration functions.

*Nursing/Clinical Staff role:* Access to encounter documentation, vital signs, medication administration records, and assigned patient care functions. Scoped to the clinical unit assignment. Cannot modify prescriptions or diagnoses without co-authorization.

*Administrative Staff role:* Access to patient registration, demographic management, scheduling, and administrative reporting. No access to clinical encounter documentation or medication records.

*IT Administrator role:* Access to OpenMRS system administration functions — user account management, system configuration, module management. No access to clinical records or patient data. Cannot view patient-identifiable information in the normal course of IT administration.

*ISSO role:* Access to audit log records and security configuration. Cannot access clinical records. Read-only access to system configuration for audit purposes.

Role permission sets are documented in the SSP appendix and reviewed annually. Changes to role permission sets require ISSO approval and are documented in the configuration change log.

**Assessment Evidence:** OpenMRS role configuration screenshots; role permission set documentation; sample of a clinical user account showing role assignment; demonstration that an administrative account cannot access clinical encounter data.

---

**AC-6: Least Privilege**

**Implementation Status:** Implemented

**Implementation Description:**

Least privilege is enforced at three layers:

*Application layer (OpenMRS roles):* As documented in AC-3 — each role is scoped to the minimum access required for the assigned function. No role grants access beyond operational necessity.

*AWS IAM layer:* AWS IAM policies follow least privilege — the EC2 instance profile has permissions only to write to CloudWatch Logs and read from the specific S3 bucket for configuration files; the backup service account has permissions only to write to the backup S3 bucket; the ISSO has read access to CloudTrail logs and Security Hub findings but cannot modify IAM policies. No IAM entity has AdministratorAccess.

*Operating system layer:* The OpenMRS application runs as a dedicated service account (openmrs-svc) on the EC2 instance with no login shell and no sudo privileges. System administration tasks require a separate privileged account with SSH key authentication, logged separately.

Quarterly review of IAM policies by ISSO to identify and remediate any privilege drift. AWS IAM Access Analyzer is enabled to identify resource policies that grant external access.

**Assessment Evidence:** AWS IAM policy documentation for each IAM entity; IAM Access Analyzer findings from most recent review; EC2 instance profile permissions; OS service account configuration.

