### System and Communications Protection (SC) — Technical Controls

---

**SC-8: Transmission Confidentiality and Integrity**

**Implementation Status:** Implemented

**Implementation Description:**

All communications between users and the OpenMRS application are encrypted using TLS. The implementation has three components:

*HTTPS enforcement:* The Apache Tomcat configuration on the EC2 instance is configured to accept connections on port 443 (HTTPS) only. HTTP connections on port 80 return a 301 redirect to the HTTPS equivalent URL. The security group for the EC2 instance permits inbound traffic on port 443 and port 80 (redirect only). No other ports accept inbound connections from the internet.

*TLS configuration:* TLS 1.2 is the minimum protocol version; TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are disabled. The cipher suite is configured to use forward secrecy — ECDHE key exchange algorithms preferred. The TLS certificate is issued by AWS Certificate Manager for the OpenMRS domain; ACM manages certificate renewal automatically. Certificate expiration is monitored via CloudWatch and alerts the ISSO 30 days before expiration.

*Internal communications:* The connection between the EC2 application server and the RDS MySQL database uses TLS encryption. The MySQL connection string in OpenMRS configuration specifies requireSSL=true; connections without TLS are rejected by the RDS parameter group configuration.

**Assessment Evidence:** Tomcat configuration showing HTTPS enforcement and HTTP redirect; security group rules; TLS version and cipher suite configuration; ACM certificate status; RDS parameter group showing SSL enforcement.

---

**SC-28: Protection of Information at Rest**

**Implementation Status:** Implemented

**Implementation Description:**

Encryption at rest is implemented across all storage components containing ePHI:

*RDS database encryption:* The OpenMRS RDS MySQL instance has encryption at rest enabled using AWS KMS with customer-managed key [key-alias/openmrs-rds-encryption]. Encryption was enabled at instance creation — it cannot be enabled on an existing unencrypted RDS instance without creating a new instance from an encrypted snapshot. All automated backups and snapshots inherit the encryption of the source instance.

*EC2 EBS volume encryption:* The root EBS volume and any data volumes attached to the OpenMRS EC2 instance are encrypted using AWS KMS with customer-managed key [key-alias/openmrs-ec2-encryption]. EC2 account-level setting requires encryption for all new EBS volumes by default.

*S3 backup bucket encryption:* The S3 bucket used for OpenMRS database backups is configured with server-side encryption using AWS KMS (SSE-KMS) with customer-managed key [key-alias/openmrs-s3-backup]. S3 bucket policy denies any PutObject requests that do not specify SSE-KMS encryption, preventing unencrypted uploads.

*KMS key management:* All three customer-managed keys are configured with annual automatic rotation. Key policies restrict key usage to authorized IAM roles only. Key usage and administrative actions are logged in CloudTrail. The ISSO reviews KMS key usage logs quarterly and confirms no unauthorized key usage.

**Assessment Evidence:** RDS instance console showing encryption enabled and KMS key identifier; EC2 console showing EBS volume encryption; S3 bucket encryption configuration and bucket policy; KMS key configuration showing customer-managed keys with rotation enabled; CloudTrail log sample showing key usage events.

