### Audit and Accountability (AU) — Technical Controls

---

**AU-2 / AU-12: Event Logging**

**Implementation Status:** Implemented

**Implementation Description:**

Audit logging for OpenMRS operates at two distinct layers that serve different purposes:

*Layer 1 — Application audit log (system-specific):*
The OpenMRS application generates audit records for all ePHI access events. The OpenMRS audit log module is configured to record: user identifier, patient identifier (internal MRN — not demographic data), record type accessed, action performed (view/create/modify), outcome, timestamp (UTC), and source IP address. These records are the primary HIPAA audit control evidence — they answer "who accessed which patient record and when."

Application audit logs are shipped via the CloudWatch Logs agent to CloudWatch log group [openmrs-application-audit] with a 6-year retention policy. The CloudWatch log group is configured with a resource policy preventing deletion of log events. IAM policies restrict who can read audit log contents to ISSO only — clinical and administrative staff cannot access audit logs.

*Layer 2 — AWS infrastructure audit log (hybrid — CloudTrail):*
AWS CloudTrail captures all AWS API calls across the account. CloudTrail is configured for all regions with management event logging enabled. CloudTrail logs are delivered to a dedicated S3 bucket [cloudtrail-logs-openmrs-[account-id]] separate from the backup bucket. Log file integrity validation is enabled — SHA-256 hash validation allows detection of any modification to log files after delivery. CloudTrail log S3 bucket has Block Public Access enabled and is not accessible to the EC2 instance role.

These two layers are complementary and distinct. CloudTrail answers "who made what AWS API call and when." The application audit log answers "which OpenMRS user accessed which patient record and when." Both are required; neither substitutes for the other.

**Assessment Evidence:** CloudWatch log group configuration showing application audit log retention and access policy; sample application audit log records showing required fields; CloudTrail configuration showing all-region logging and integrity validation; CloudTrail S3 bucket policy; demonstration that IAM policy restricts application audit log access to ISSO.

---

**AU-9: Protection of Audit Information**

**Implementation Status:** Implemented

**Implementation Description:**

Audit records are protected from unauthorized access, modification, and deletion through three mechanisms:

*CloudWatch log group protection:* The application audit log group [openmrs-application-audit] has a resource-based policy that denies DeleteLogGroup and DeleteLogStream actions to all principals except the designated audit administrator role. IAM policies further restrict write access to the CloudWatch Logs agent running on the EC2 instance. ISSO has read access; no other role has access to audit log contents.

*CloudTrail log integrity:* CloudTrail log file integrity validation generates a signed digest file every hour. If any log file is modified, deleted, or forged after delivery, the digest file validation fails. ISSO validates CloudTrail log integrity monthly using the AWS CLI validation command; results documented in the audit log review record.

*S3 bucket protection for CloudTrail logs:* S3 Object Lock is enabled on the CloudTrail log bucket in compliance mode with a retention period equal to the required log retention period. This prevents deletion or modification of log files during the retention period even by the root account.

Any attempt to delete or modify audit records generates a CloudWatch alert configured on the CloudTrail event for DeleteLogGroup, PutBucketPolicy on the log bucket, or changes to the CloudTrail configuration.

**Assessment Evidence:** CloudWatch log group resource policy; CloudTrail integrity validation records from most recent monthly check; S3 Object Lock configuration on CloudTrail bucket; CloudWatch alarm configuration for audit tampering events.

