## A Note on SSP as a Diagnostic Tool

While drafting today's implementation descriptions, two gaps surfaced that I want to document explicitly:

**Gap 1 — Application audit log review process:** The AU-2 implementation documents that application audit logs are collected and retained. The Day 30 monitoring strategy defined a weekly manual log review. But the AU-6(1) enhancement from Day 47 requires automated audit analysis for anomaly detection, not just weekly manual review. The SSP writing exercise surfaced that the automated CloudWatch metric filters for application audit log anomalies have not yet been fully specified — what constitutes an anomalous access pattern, at what threshold, triggering what alert. This is a planned enhancement that needs to be added to the Plan of Action and Milestones before authorization.

**Gap 2 — TLS certificate monitoring:** The SC-8 implementation documents that the ISSO is alerted 30 days before certificate expiration. The CloudWatch alarm for this monitoring has not yet been configured. This is a straightforward configuration task but needs to be tracked to completion.

Both of these gaps were discovered through SSP writing, not through a separate gap analysis exercise. This is exactly what NIST SP 800-18 means when it describes the SSP as a living document — writing it surfaces operational detail that needs to be addressed. I will add both items to the POA&M.

