## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While working through the audit log implementation descriptions today I returned to the **2015 Anthem breach** — which I covered on Day 35 — specifically to look at it through the SSP documentation lens.

Anthem's breach resulted in the exposure of nearly 79 million records. Post-incident investigation found that Anthem had not implemented robust database activity monitoring — the controls that would have generated audit records of the unusual database query patterns the attacker used to extract records. The attackers used a valid administrative credential to run queries that extracted large volumes of data over several weeks before discovery.

The specific gap that today's work addresses: had Anthem's SSP required an implementation description for AU-2 at the specificity level I documented above — including "which events are logged," "where logs are stored," "how logs are protected," and "how anomalous patterns generate alerts" — the writing exercise would have surfaced the absence of database activity monitoring as a gap. The SSP would have either documented a planned control (adding it to the POA&M) or prompted implementation before the authorization was approved.

The SSP is not just documentation of what was done. It is a forcing function for honest accounting of what has not been done. An SSP written to the specificity standard I am applying today would have made Anthem's monitoring gap visible — and visible gaps can be remediated.

